commit.message:
[ci] Update to actions/checkout@v4

Should fix warnings from GHA, and allows making use of new option
to not log a lot of progress messages from git.

Don't warn about c_functionend not being reachable

This is a special node that represents the end of the function so
isn't really unreachable snowball code.

Adjust wording of unreachable code warnings

Saying "unreachable" seems less jargon-y than "dead code", and also
matches the terminology Java's error message uses.

Use $(patsubst ...) instead of sed

This gives cleaner make output and is a bit more efficient.
GNUmakefile: Tidy up and make more consistent

GNUmakefile: Simplify further

The previous change to use $* means we no longer need to mess around
with temporary variables, @ to hide over-complex commands, and echo-ing
the command ourselves.

GNUmakefile: Make use of $*

This avoids needing to echo $< into sed to extract the same string,
which was slower and less readable.
Fix typo in README files

[java] Only emit methodObject when it's used

See #195

commit.message:
improve TestApp to create less objects

I tried to keep it simple here, but doing a rough measurement of `time make check_java` x 3 gives the idea:

```
before:

real  0m24.713s
user  0m39.545s
sys 0m1.962s

real  0m24.992s
user  0m39.570s
sys 0m2.082s

real  0m24.166s
user  0m38.705s
sys 0m1.842s

after:

real  0m20.365s
user  0m31.869s
sys 0m1.781s

real  0m20.593s
user  0m32.733s
sys 0m1.858s

real  0m20.576s
user  0m32.992s
sys 0m1.763s
```

This mini-benchmark of the tests isn't indicative of typical performance, it is bottlenecked by JVM startup cost for each language.

commit.message: CONTRIBUTING.rst: Go into more detail

Track shortest string in each among in analyser

This refactor eliminates duplicate code from the C and Ada generators,
and means this data is available to other generators that want to use
it.

[ada] Use analyser->name_count[name_type]

This eliminates some ada-specific code which iterates over all the names
to rediscover this information.

[python] Specify python_requires

Indicate to install tools that the generated code won't work with Python
3.0.x, 3.1.x and 3.2.x (due to use of `u"foo"` string literals).

Closes #192 and #191, opened by Andreas Maier.

[python] Add classifier to indicate Python 3.3 support

In doc/libstemmer_python_README we say "Python 3 (>= 3.3) is supported"
(which is because we generate literal strings with a `u` prefix) so
update the classifier list to include it for consistency.

See #192
Fix comment typo

Fix line number for "string not terminated" error

The reported line number was one too high in the case where we
were in a stringdef (but correct if we weren't).

[german] Don't remove -em if preceded by -syst

Previously we would overstem words ending -system.  This change means
we now conflate e.g. "system" and "systemen".

See #161

Document input should be lowercase with composed accents

See #186

turkish: Adjust stringdefs to match other uses

Use {sc} for s-cedilla and {i} for dotless-i.

estonian: Use recommended latin stringdef codes

Using common codes makes it easier to work across algorithms, but
they are more mnemonic so also seem clearer when just considering this
one algorithm.

lithuanian:Use recommended latin stringdef codes

Using common codes makes it easier to work across algorithms, but
they are more mnemonic so also seem clearer when just considering this
one algorithm.

serban.sbl: Use recommended latin stringdef codes

Using common codes makes it easier to work across algorithms, but
they are more mnemonic so also seem clearer when just considering this
one algorithm.
[ci] Sort out handling of PRs
